  "school": "ICT",
  "definition": "A price range divided by the 50% Fibonacci level (equilibrium): the upper half is premium (overvalued, favoring shorts), the lower half is discount (undervalued, favoring longs). The range can be based on swing points, displacement legs, consolidation ranges, or opening prices. Deeper price into premium/discount offers better risk-reward.",
  "identification_rules": [
    "Identify a significant price range (e.g., swing high/low, displacement range, consolidation range, Asia/London range, or midnight 0:00 and 8:30 open levels).",
    "Apply Fibonacci retracement tool between the range high and low; the 0.5 level is the equilibrium (EQ).",
    "The area above the 0.5 level is premium; the area below is discount.",
    "When price is above both 0:00 and 8:30 opens, it is deep premium; below both is deep discount.",
    "Update the premium/discount range when price makes a new high or low.",
    "Apply on multiple timeframes: higher timeframe determines direction, lower timeframe for entry.",
    "Use additional Fibonacci levels (0.62, 0.79) within premium/discount to refine optimal trade entry (OTE) zones."
  ],
  "trading_implication": "In discount, prioritize long setups at price delivery arrays (order blocks, fair value gaps); in premium, prioritize short setups. Deeper price into premium/discount offers better risk-reward; entries near equilibrium have ~1:1 risk-reward. Use with market structure shifts and liquidity sweeps for high-probability entries. Also use premium/discount as targets: long targets premium, short targets discount. Dynamically update ranges.",
  "common_mistakes": [
    "Confusing direction: premium favors shorts, discount favors longs.",
    "Incorrectly identifying range boundaries (should be based on swing points, displacement, or clear structure).",
    "Failing to update range when price makes new highs/lows.",
    "Mixing multiple nested ranges without marking each equilibrium.",
    "Treating premium/discount as fixed support/resistance instead of relative to a range.",
    "Relying solely on premium/discount without confluences (FVG, order block, market structure).",
    "Entering near equilibrium ignoring poor risk-reward.",
    "Confusing external and internal liquidity when drawing range.",
    "Not updating premium/discount based on higher timeframe order flow.",
    "Using only one open level for deep premium/discount (need both 0:00 and 8:30)."
  ],
